    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.62-63_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">62</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        175 West 93rd Street 
                        New York 25, New York
                        March 11, 1959
                    </dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>c/o Petri</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>Route 5</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Sorry that I have not written sooner, but many things have come up to delay my work on the article. I have taken notes from Mrs. Aly's thesis and will mail the thesis back to you this week. I will also write Mrs. Aly in care of you, giving my impression of her work.</p>
                
                <p>Right now, I am engaged in a major effort. I was asked to work on the book for a musical comedy. The composer with whom I am working was formerly official pianist, organist and harpsichordist for the New York Philharmonic. I have been working every night after coming home from my regular job. This past Sunday, we had an audition with John Shubert, New York's leading theatre owner, and he was quite impressed. He is going to arrange for us to audition for potential producers. If I am successful in this effort, the contacts that I make will really put me in a position to push "The Song of Three Friends."</p>
                
                <p>I have outlined my prospective article, and as soon as the turmoil abates, I will get back to work.</p>
                
                <p>Enough about me -- Both Adele and I were greatly pleased that your trip to the Coast turned out so well. We were not surprised, though, that you found friends there. Few places exist in this country where you would not find a following or be able to develop one quickly. We are still hoping that you will get a chance to come East, so that we can repay your hospitality.</p>
                
                <p>Take good care of yourself, and I promise the next letter will not be so long in coming. Regards to your family.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Your good friends,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Bob &amp; Adele</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
  
